Generics let you parameterize types so code stays reusable without losing type safety.

**Constrained generics** — restrict what T can be:

```typescript
function getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {
  return obj[key];
}
const user = { name: "Ana", age: 30 };
getProperty(user, "name"); // string
getProperty(user, "foo");  // compile error
```

**Mapped types** — transform every property:

```typescript
type Readonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] };
type Optional<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] };
```

**Generic classes** — typed collections:

```typescript
class TypedMap<K, V> {
  private store = new Map<K, V>();
  set(key: K, value: V) { this.store.set(key, value); }
  get(key: K): V | undefined { return this.store.get(key); }
}
const scores = new TypedMap<string, number>();
scores.set("alice", 95);
```

**Conditional types** — type-level branching:

```typescript
type Unwrap<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? U : T;
type A = Unwrap<Promise<string>>; // string
type B = Unwrap<number>;          // number
```

**Factory pattern** — construct instances generically:

```typescript
function create<T>(ctor: new (...args: any[]) => T, ...args: any[]): T {
  return new ctor(...args);
}
